er to provide correct inputs."},"36":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-5","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"Otherwise, there is no sense in even starting any service processing."},"37":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-6","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"Also errors are often semantically close to the exceptions."},"38":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-7","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"In other words, service errors are frequently located at the same places where exceptions are raised/rescued in the reqular methods."},"39":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-8","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"Exceptional behaviour like HTTP connection issues, database inconsistencies, timeouts, etc are also errors."},"40":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-9","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"Check out the following example:"},"41":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-10","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"And this is how it can be triggerred:"},"42":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-11","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"There is no point to involve all the heavy machinery when the feature name is nil."},"43":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-12","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"Why do we need to waste any expensive resources if the feature name is unknown?"},"44":{"id":"/docs/basics/errors-13","page_id":"/docs/basics/errors","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/errors#what-is-an-error","content":"Can we guarantee whe