":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"So when the service is invoked, but the ticket is not ordered for some logical business reason, it should be treated as a failure."},"54":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-7","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"Why?"},"55":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-8","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"Business reason is not an error, since the input is valid, the environment is stable, but the service goal is still not achieved."},"56":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-9","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"Please, read the following code snippet carefully to get the idea."},"57":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-10","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"And this is how it can be triggerred:"},"58":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-11","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"When the bus is nil we can not even try to order a ticket."},"59":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-12","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"When the bus does not have a valid number, we can not even try to order a ticket."},"60":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-13","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"When an exception is raised, we can not complete the ticket order due to the technical issue."},"61":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-14","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"Hence errors are returned for those cases."},"62":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-15","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"But once all the validation preconditions are met and exceptions are avoided, the ticket can still not be ordered for business reasons."},"63":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-16","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"This is the place when failures come into play."},"64":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-17","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"The lack of available seats or the trip delay are examples of business reasons."},"65":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-18","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"Just accept the fact that at the given moment in time, there is no possibility to order a ticket for that specific bus."},"66":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-19","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"But the crucial point is that a failure is a strong and reliable explainer of why the desired effect hasn't happened."},"67":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-20","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"That is one of the key difference between errors and failures."},"68":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-21","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"Errors give you no service goal resolution at all."},"69":{"id":"/docs/basics/failures-22","page_id":"/docs/basics/failures","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/failures#what-is-a-failure","content":"While failures provide a stable negative service goal resolution that is a strong foundation for the subsequent decision-making."},"70":{"id":"/docs/basics","page_id":"/docs/basics","type":"page","content":"Basics","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Basics"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics"},"71":{"id":"/docs/basics-0","page_id":"/docs/basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics","content":"Convenient Service Basics."},"72":{"id":"/docs/basics-1","page_id":"/docs/basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics","content":"What is a service?"},"73":{"id":"/docs/basics-2","page_id":"/docs/basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics","content":"What is a result?"},"74":{"id":"/docs/basics-3","page_id":"/docs/basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics","content":"Which result types are available?"},"75":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","type":"page","content":"Result Types","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Basics"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/result_types"},"76":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-0","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"Success, failure, and error"},"77":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-1","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"Results in the wild"},"78":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-2","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"The are 3 types of results in Convenient Service - success, failure, and error."},"79":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-3","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"The simplest way to explain them is based on a comparison to the regular methods."},"80":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-4","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"Therefore, the definition may be the following:"},"81":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-5","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"The success results are returned from services exactly at the same cases when the expected values are returned from the regular methods."},"82":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-6","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"The failure results are returned from services exactly at the same cases when the fallback values are returned from the regular methods."},"83":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-7","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"The error results are returned from services exactly at the same cases when the exceptions are raised from the regular methods."},"84":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-8","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"So, basically, the main difference between the failure and error results is whether to continue or stop the process when something is not successful just like between fallbacks and exceptions in the regular methods."},"85":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-9","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"For boolean methods \"fallback\" values are false and nil."},"86":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-10","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#success-failure-and-error","content":"For void methods \"fallbacks\" are returns before the desired side-effect is applied."},"87":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-11","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"Let's check some real-world examples of the methods with both fallbacks and exceptions and see how they may look like with Convenient Service results."},"88":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-12","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"Context#context_superclass method taken from Hanami."},"89":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-13","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"CommentVisitor#process? method taken from Rails."},"90":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-14","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"ResponseBuilder#perform method taken from Chatwood."},"91":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-15","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"Entry#extract method taken from GitLab."},"92":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-16","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"DistributedCache#defer_get_set from Discourse."},"93":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-17","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"After a careful review of all those methods:"},"94":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-18","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"Can you see a common pattern of how people decide between fallbacks and exceptions?"},"95":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-19","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"Does this pattern look uniformly reproducible?"},"96":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-20","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"Can you explain it to the beginner devs so that they can apply it the same way all the time?"},"97":{"id":"/docs/basics/result_types-21","page_id":"/docs/basics/result_types","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/result_types#results-in-the-wild","content":"That is why Convenient Service try to use the notion of the service goals."},"98":{"id":"/docs/basics/results","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","type":"page","content":"Results","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Basics"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/results"},"99":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-0","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Motivation behind results"},"100":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-1","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/results#so-what-is-a-result-its-benefits","content":"So what is a Result? Its benefits?"},"101":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-2","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Usually, the service exposes a sole public method, let it be call for this case."},"102":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-3","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Since Ruby is a dynamic language, call may return any type of value."},"103":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-4","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Sometimes it is advantageous, for things like Duck Typing, Abstract Factories, Null Objects, etc."},"104":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-5","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"But occasionally it may also become problematic."},"105":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-6","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"For example, you can not implement a unified way to check whether the value was calculated correctly (as it was intended by its author)."},"106":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-7","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Someone may consider Object#blank? and its opposite Object#present? from ActiveSupport as an attempt, but they detect truthiness in the Rails sense."},"107":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-8","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Also it is common to forget to verify if the returned value is actually what you need:"},"108":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-9","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Convenient Service suggests utilizing Result objects as a way to overcome the problems listed above."},"109":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-10","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Practically speaking, to return results from all services."},"110":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-11","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"To express this idea, let's create a different public method instead of call and name it result."},"111":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-12","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#motivation-behind-results","content":"Now, we have the following invocation:"},"112":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-13","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#so-what-is-a-result-its-benefits","content":"Result is a data structure that satisfies the following properties:"},"113":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-14","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#so-what-is-a-result-its-benefits","content":"Firstly, it has a consolidated way to detect its state (success?, failure?, error?, and their counterparts with not like not_success?)."},"114":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-15","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#so-what-is-a-result-its-benefits","content":"Secondly, when the result is successful, you can be 100% sure that its data is correct, no additional verifications are needed (the notion of correctness is defined by the service author)."},"115":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-16","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#so-what-is-a-result-its-benefits","content":"Moveover, results induce you to always check them, before accessing their attributes, otherwise an exception is raised."},"116":{"id":"/docs/basics/results-17","page_id":"/docs/basics/results","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/results#so-what-is-a-result-its-benefits","content":"Also, when something goes wrong, the result contains a description of the reason (result.message), which simplifies finding the source of the problem."},"117":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","type":"page","content":"Service goals","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Basics"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/service_goals"},"118":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-0","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"What is a service goal?"},"119":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-1","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#service-goal-resolutions","content":"Service goal resolutions"},"120":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-2","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals","content":"To get an idea of the result types better, let's introduce an auxiliary term - service goal."},"121":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-3","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"The service goal is the desired effect of an action/operation."},"122":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-4","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"What does it mean in practise?"},"123":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-5","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"Imagine the service below:"},"124":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-6","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"Its desired effect is the found user record."},"125":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-7","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"Simple and straightforward."},"126":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-8","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"So, if you are a developer who wants to utilize this service, the only reason why you would decide to do it is to get the user record."},"127":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-9","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"Thus the following conclusion can be made."},"128":{"id":"/docs/basics/service_goals-10","page_id":"/docs/basics/service_goals","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/basics/service_goals#what-is-a-service-goal","content":"We always invoke a service to achieve some concrete goal defined by the service author."},"129":{"id":"/